### References in Rust

A reference is a pointer that follows the borrowing rules. References are created with the `&` operator and dereferenced with `*`.

---

### Reference Types

| Type | Syntax | Description |
|------|--------|-------------|
| Immutable reference | `&T` | Read-only access |
| Mutable reference | `&mut T` | Read-write access |

---

### Dereferencing

```rust
let x = 5;
let y = &x;  // y is a reference to x

assert_eq!(x, 5);
assert_eq!(*y, 5);  // dereference to get the value

// Auto-dereferencing
// Rust automatically dereferences when calling methods
let s = String::from("hello");
let r = &s;
println!("{}", r.len());   // auto-deref: (*r).len()
println!("{}", (*r).len()); // explicit deref

// Mutable reference
let mut z = 10;
let z_ref = &mut z;
*z_ref = 20;  // dereference to mutate
println!("{}", z);  // 20
```

> **Key Point:** Rust automatically dereferences references when calling methods or accessing fields, so you rarely need the `*` operator explicitly. This is called auto-dereferencing.

codeExample:
fn main() {
    let mut value = 42;

    let ref1 = &value;
    let ref2 = &value;
    println!("ref1: {}, ref2: {}", ref1, ref2);
    // ref1 and ref2 go out of scope here

    let ref_mut = &mut value;
    *ref_mut += 10;
    println!("value after mutable ref: {}", value);
}
